<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Response to Reducing Re-Offending in London and NOMS Regional Commissioning</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Written Evidence from Clinks [PUB0016]</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">About Clinks</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Clinks is the national infrastructure organisation supporting Voluntary, Community and Social Enterprise (VCSE) Sector organisations working with offenders and their families. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Founded in 1993</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and registered as a charity in 1998</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, w</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e are a mem</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">bership organ</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">isation with over 6</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">00 Members including the Sector’s largest providers as well as its smallest</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Our vision </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">is of a vibrant and independent VCSE Sector working with informed and engaged communities to enable the rehabilitation of offenders.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:#0093bb; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Clinks welcomes this timely inquiry into public service reform. As might be expected, we are in support of the Government’s “ambition to distribute power and opportunity to people”, and specifically of greater involvement of the VCSE Sector in the running </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">of public services. The VCSE Sector not only has valuable knowledge and experience of delivering services at community level, but also often has the advantage of strong relationships with members of society who </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">may be</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> distrustful of statutory services. We </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">believe this means that they have an important contribution to make at all stages of designing and delivering services.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Our </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">M</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">embers work with </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">offenders, ex-offenders and their families</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. In our view, it is important to remember that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">those who have been con</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">victed of offences still remain citizens</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, as their families unquestionably </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">do</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">; at times, this risks being forgotten in the political and media debates on crime. It is in society’s interests that interventions for offenders are as effective and accountable </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">as any other public service.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In this context, Clinks has raised some concerns about the implications and pace of the current Transforming Rehabilitation plans for the future of probation</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. We are in favour of decisive action to help reduce reoffending, in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">cluding the extension of supervision to offenders ending sentences of 12 months or less, and we welcome the stated commitment to including the VCSE Sector as part of the reforms.  However, we have unanswered questions about whether this will translate into</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> practice. For this reason, parts of our answers below focus specifically on this agenda.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Summary </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The VCSE Sector is made up of active citizens participating in service delivery at community level. Despite welcome commitments from government that the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Sector should have more opportunities as a result of major reforms such as the Transforming Rehabilitation probation agenda, we are concerned by signs that this may not happen in practice. G</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">reater involvement of the Sector does not happen automatically sim</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ply because services are opened up to new providers; it requires a firm steer to commissioners and lead providers. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Particular challenges are faced by smaller organisations in meeting the challenges of a Payment by Results system. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Wherever possible, Clink</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s would recommend that subcontracted VCSE partners carrying out discrete pieces of work should receive 100% of their delivery fee upfront. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">At the very least, Clinks is keen to see firm commitments, and ideally a cap on risk</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> transfer</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, stipulated as part of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the contracts</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">What’s more, true empowerment of citizens goes beyond merely delivering services: it must include the ability to highlight good and bad practice and influence future policy.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Clinks is keen to know what structures will be put into place to e</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nsure that the VCSE retains an indep</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">endent voice both to the Tier 1 providers under Transforming Rehabilitation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and to government.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Clinks is also concerned that the reforms should focus on outcomes in line with the realities of how people desist from crim</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In particular, the binary hurdle</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">- whereby p</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">roviders do not get paid at all if they do not achieve a reduction in the total percentage of offenders who reoffend within a one-year period</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">- risks skewing the Tier 1</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> provider</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s’ priorities away from those </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">interventions which may be most effective in the longer term.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> We </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">would therefore like to see more focus on intermediate outcomes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> those factors which have an impact on the road to desistance, even if they do not immediately lead to reduced reoffending.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> In </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">particular, the newly-announced option of grants by Tier 1 providers to VCSE partners are an opportunity to promote intermediate outcomes. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">More broadly, we believe that the many recent changes in this area in a short time, including Police and Crime Comm</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">issioners as well as Transforming Rehabilitation, not only </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">exacerbate the challenges to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">co-commissioning and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> involvement</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> of the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">VCSE Sector, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">but also risk</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> conflicting sets of priorities for the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">riminal </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">J</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ustice </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">S</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ystem</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Finally, we suggest that key el</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ements of good, accountably public services are service user involvement and multi-agency partnership working, and we would urge greater promotion of these as Transforming Rehabilitation rolls out.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Question </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">1. To what extent is the Government’s public ser</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">vice reform programme succeeding in: </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">a)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">empowering citizens?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The VCSE Sector relies upon the active participation of citizens, as both staff and volunteers, and so Clinks believes that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the Sector’s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">greater involvement in public service delivery is inherentl</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">y empowering to individuals and communities. Transforming Rehabilitation aims to broaden out the market in probation services, with the explicit intention of increasing the diversity of providers, including from the VCSE Sector.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">However, it is unclear </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">whether this will be the reality. There are signs that fewer VCSE organisations than anticipated may end up engaging with the new service landscape, and that the result may thus be a narrowing of the current range of providers, in direct opposition to the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Government’s intentions. At the time of writing, just 387 self-declared VCSE organisation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> had signed up to the Ministry of Justice’s Prior Information Notice;  Clinks’ own membership is over 600, and the Centre for Social Justice estimates that there are </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a total of 1,475 organisations in the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">S</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ector </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">whose primary service user group is offenders, ex-offenders and their families</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Similarly, Clinks’ analysis of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">p</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">olice and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">c</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rime </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">c</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ommissioners’ police and crime plans for 2013/14 shows that 18 plans make no mention of the VCSE Sector as potential delivery partners and 29 make no mention of the Sector as a strategic partner, indicating that the introduction of elected PCCs has not led</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to greater involvement of the Sector in the running of public services. The clear lesson seems to be that greater involvement of the Sector does not happen automatically simply because services are opened up to new providers; it requires a firm steer to c</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ommissioners and lead providers. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">What’s more, true empowerment of citizens goes beyond merely delivering services: it must include the ability to highlight good and bad practice and influence future policy. This is in fact a core part of the Sector’s ide</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ntity, both in their own eyes and those of the public, as the recent controversy around the Transparency of Lobbying, Non-Party Campaigning and Trade Union Administration Bill demonstrates</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. The involvement of the VCSE Sector in Transforming Rehabilitation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> is likely to be concentrated at Tiers 2 or 3, given the size and financial resources needed to bid as a Tier 1 (or prime) provider. But if organisations are confined to supply chains without also being given an advocacy role in how Tier 1 operates, and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">if</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">there is little remaining relationship with government other than an indirect commercial one, then the risk is that they will in fact be less powerful than before. For this reason, Clinks is keen to know what structures will be put in place to ensure that</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the VCSE</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Sector</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> retains an independent voice both to the Tier 1</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> providers</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and to government.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">b)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">improving public services</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In Clinks’ and our </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">M</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">embers’ </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">experience, good services for offenders which work to promote reduced reoffending cannot be separated from</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> an understanding of desistance theory. Desistance theory is the academic study of how people desist from crime</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> it distinguishes between primary desistance, meaning any lull or gap in offending, however short-lived, and secondary desistance, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">which refers </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to a more deep-seated change in an individual where they develop an identity as a ‘non-offender’.  </span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The VCSE Sector has successfully developed and promoted an approach to rehabilitation and resettlement services that takes account of desistance theory: th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">is takes the form of holistic, flexible and person-centred support that, crucially, is not time-limited, reflecting that the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">journey towards secondary desistance is highly individualised and very likely to involve relapses. Clinks has recently produced a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> g</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">uide </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">for</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the Sector on how to promote desistance which the Committee may find useful</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">However, we are concerned that the proposed Payment by Results (PbR) system that will be used as part of Transforming Rehabilitation does not reflect the reality of des</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">istance from crime. In particular, the binary hurdle</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">- whereby p</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">roviders </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">do not</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> get paid at all if they do not achieve a reduction in the total percentage of offenders who reoffend</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">- risks skewing the Tier 1s’ priorities away from those interventions which</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> may be most effective in the longer term.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Clinks would therefore like to see more focus on intermediate outcomes: those factors which have an impact on the road to desistance, even if they do not immediately lead to reduced reoffending. These include the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> attitudes and behaviour of service users, and factors like their mental health, wellbeing, family relations and employment and accommodation. Many VCSE organisations specialise in delivering these outcomes, and the National Offender Management Service (NO</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">MS) have sought to provide information on their effectiveness</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, but this is no guarantee that Tier 1</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> providers </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s will invest in services that promote them. Clinks would like to see a more robust requirement for them to do so.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">c)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">ensuring that public services</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold"> are accountable to the people who use them, and to elected officials?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Within the VCSE Sector working in criminal justice and embedded in academic desistance theory is a widespread recognition and growing evidence that involving offenders, ex-offenders, t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">heir families or carers can improve the services they use. Because of their direct experiences of services, service users know better than anyone what works – and what does not. Involving them brings unique insights and taps into a valuable resource. Servi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ce user involvement can also have a positive impact on the individuals involved by boosting their confidence and skills. This can lead to other opportunities such as training or employment, and may therefore impact on their desistance from crime.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">However,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> service user involvement is not as widespread as Clinks would like it to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">be</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, and certainly is not embedded in public service delivery for offenders and their families. In 2011 Clinks undertook research which showed that service user involvement was more w</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">idespread in prisons than probation, which is of particular relevance now that probation services for low and medium risk offenders are to be contracted out to new providers.  Clinks has called for mechanisms for service user involvement to be embedded in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Transforming Rehabilitation contracts, but as yet no details have emerged on whether this will be prioritised.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Question </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">5. How successful have the Government’s reforms been in opening up public services to grassroots community groups rather than to large </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">private or third sector organisations?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The VCSE Sector working in criminal justice is very diverse. It includes large national providers but is predominantly made up of small, local organisations. Centre for Social Justice research has found that a quarte</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">r of VCSE organisations working in criminal justice reported to have no full time equivalent employees and just over half have an annual turnover or income of £150,000 or less.</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">A lack of upfront service delivery fees, delayed payments, and the requireme</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nt to undertake significant levels of financial risk are thus considerable barriers to smaller VCSE</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Sector</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> delivery partners hoping to enter into any contract that includes a Payment by Results element.  A survey conducted by NCVO into the experiences of V</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">CS</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">E Sector</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> providers in the DWP</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">’s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Work Programme found that the majority had experienced cash flow problems as a result of their participation and a large number claimed to be subsiding delivery from their organisation’s reserves.  The crux of the problem </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">appeared to be the delayed payment mechanism which, combined with the difficulty of predicting the number of referrals, made financial planning extremely challenging for subcontracted partners.</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">As part of Transforming Rehabilitation, the Ministry of Just</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ice have published principles of competition and market stewardship which include a requirement on Tier 1 providers not to pass down disproportionate levels of financial risk. However it is not yet clear what the definition of disproportionate is and there</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> is concern that if risk levels are too high this will preclude the involvement of smaller providers.  Wherever possible, Clinks would recommend that subcontracted VCSE partners carrying out discrete pieces of work should receive 100% of their delivery fee</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> upfront. At the very least, Clinks is keen to see firm commitments, and ideally a cap on risk</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> transfer</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, stipulated as part of the contracts: we have as yet received no indication whether it will be mentioned at all.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The documents available so far also </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">provide for the possibility of grants to be made to organisations. While this is very welcome and could provide the opportunity needed by small local organisations to get involved, as well as to promote intermediate desistance outcomes as set out under 1b </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">above, Clinks is concerned that there is a lack of clarity around the size and length of these grants and a lack of experience amongst potential Tier 1 providers in this area.  In addition, the possibility of grants does not ensure their use and there is c</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">oncern that Tier 1 providers may chose to ignore this option, which we would expect to prohibit the involvement of many smaller, local providers in the competition.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Question </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">6. How well do different tiers of government or different parts of single public </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">sector organisation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">, at central, local authority or district councils level, work together to deliver public services?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The commissioning and delivery of services for offenders and their families have been subject to a huge amount of change over a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">relatively short period of time. We have seen the introduction of elected police and crime commissioners (PCCs) and the transfer of community safety budgets from Community Safety Partnerships at local authority level to PCCs. We have also seen a reorganisa</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">tion of health services for offenders and a split in responsibility for substance misuse across PCCs and Directors of Public Health. Transforming Rehabilitation is merely the latest in a series of seismic changes to services for offenders.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Each of these d</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ifferent areas of service operate across different geographical areas: for example, the Transforming Rehabilitation Contract Package Areas (CPAs) do not match up with PCC areas, which means that there will be challenges for co-commissioning. Not only does </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">this exacerbate the service delivery challenges to the VCSE Sector, who must work very hard to build a vast number of new relationships, but it also risks conflicting sets of priorities for the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">riminal </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">J</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ustice </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">S</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ystem</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. It is particularly noticeable that, w</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">hile policing and community safety responsibilities have been devolved to the local level through PCCs, rehabilitation services are in fact becoming more centralised, since the new probation providers will be directly commissioned by central government. It</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> is not yet clear how consistency in services and policy will be ensured across this divide.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Question </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">7. What examples are there of innovative ways to deliver better public services, from other countries or from other public service providers?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">There have</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> been a number of models developed in recent years that seek to utilise ‘good’ partnership working to develop support for rehabilitation (among other outcomes).</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Integrated Offender Management is an overarching framework that brings local partners and agen</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">cies together to provide a multi-agency approach to the management of offenders whose crimes cause the most damage and harm locally. The model involves all partners tackling offenders together (both criminal justice and non-criminal justice agencies, inclu</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ding the VCSE Sector</span><a name="_ftnref8"></a><a href="#_ftn8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">), delivering a local response to local problems.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Similarly, Making Every Adult Matter</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s pilots were set up to improve coordination of services for people dealing with a combination of homelessness, substance misuse, mental health pro</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">blems and offending behaviour. These individuals have ineffective contact with services and often live </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">chaotic lives at the margins of our communities. Each pilot employed a coordinator to engage with clients, build trust and ensure the best possible route</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> through existing services. Coordinators were supported by an Operational Group and Board of local services, which helped to ensure strategic engagement and enable all agencies to provide flexible responses for clients.</span><a name="_ftnref9"></a><a href="#_ftn9">[9]</a></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="29" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Finally,  the Transition to Adulth</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ood </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">(T2A) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">pilots were aimed at giving prominence and priority to services for young adults in the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">riminal </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">J</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ustice </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">S</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ystem, recognising that this is a stage in life </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">that involves many of the most challenging developments and adjustments, and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">when those alre</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ady involved in offending are at risk of becoming the most prolific. They aimed to promote a local inter-agency system for guiding young adults into better lives</span><a name="_ftnref10"></a><a href="#_ftn10">[10]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> through the provision of a T2A worker to build trusting relationships with service users and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">through meetings between agencies to support joint decision making processes.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="30" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">All of these models, by their very nature, are based on multi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">agency responses to individuals</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> needs allowing them to provide holistic responses and eliminate divisions between </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">services.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Question </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">8. How realistic is it that ‘choice’ can be exercised in public service provision or should we be looking instead at greater control by users so they can ensure that public services become more responsive to changing needs?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">8.a How do </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">we make sure that all citizens are able to influence public services?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="31" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Statutory services for offenders by their very nature do not offer ‘choice’. However</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> many offenders and ex-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">offender</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> do cho</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">se to access additional services outside of statutory provis</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ion and these are often delivered by the VCSE Sector. These are particularly important in the longer-term, after supervision requirements have ended, to help offenders who have not ye</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">t achieved secondary desistance (and for whom intermediate outcomes are t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">herefore crucial).</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> As set out above, Clinks believes that it is essential for user involvement to be part of how services are designed as part of Transforming Rehabil</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">itation.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> This should also include those services which are not mandatory, whether these ar</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e commissioned as part of the new structures or elsewhere, to ensure that this vital level of additional support does not become </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">endangered</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Question </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">10. How do we ensure that best practice so it can be replicated in the context of greater diversity of pr</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ovision?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="32" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">As set out above, the VCSE Sector must retain the ability to promote best practice without this being limited by their role in a supply chain. For this reason, both commissioners and the Government need to ensure the necessary structures</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> are </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">place to ensure direct consultation with the Sector.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Question </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">11. How well has the system of Payment by Results worked in the delivery of public services and how do we make it work better?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="33" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">As set out, a significant risk of Payment by Results is that it may squeeze VCSE organisations out of public service delivery, particularly smaller organisations. Where possible, Clinks would recommend the implementation of a PbR model in which subcontract</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ed VCS partners receive 100% of their delivery costs upfront, with the outcomes risk borne by the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Tier 1</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">or an external investor.  One example of this is the Social Impact Bond model (SIB) used in the PbR pilot at HMP Peterborough.  Here, social investment</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> funds are pooled in a Special Purpose Vehicle </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">(partnership or limited company) which contracts with VCS providers to deliver innovative resettlement support to short term prisoners.  The VCS providers are paid 100% upfront and all risk is carried by the i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nvestors, who also receive a return on investment from Government proportionate to the outcomes achieved.</span><a name="_ftnref11"></a><a href="#_ftn11">[11]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="34" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Where it is not possible to implement the social investment model, Clinks would recommend that no more than </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">20%</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> of the total contracted fee should </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">be left at risk.  This is the structure of the PbR pilot at HMP Doncaster, where the full payment is made to the prime each year with 10% at risk, to be repaid in the event of failure to reduce reoffending by the targeted amount.  This release of working c</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">apital would allow a diverse range of providers to bid as </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Tier 1 providers</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">or as sub-contractors for PbR contracts within adult </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">criminal justice</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">services, or to participate in partnership consortia, while maintaining the incentive to achieve outcomes.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="35" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">It </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">is clear, however, that even a figure of 20% would represent an unfeasible level of risk for many VCS organisations.  Wherever possible, Clinks would recommend that subcontracted VCS partners carrying out discrete pieces of work should receive 100% of thei</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">r delivery fee upfront.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal">November 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><a href="http://www.justice.gov.uk/transforming-rehabilitation"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.justice.gov.uk/transforming-rehabilitation</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><a href="http://www.centreforsocialjustice.org.uk/UserStorage/pdf/Pdf%20reports/probationnew.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.centreforsocialjustice.org.uk/UserStorage/pdf/Pdf%20reports/probationnew.pdf</span></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><a href="http://services.parliament.uk/bills/2013-14/transparencyoflobbyingnonpartycampaigningandtradeunionadministration.html"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://services.parliament.uk/bills/2013-14/transparencyoflobbyingnonpartycampaigningandtradeunionadministration.html</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn4"></a><a href="#_ftnref4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><a href="http://www.clinks.org/sites/default/files/null/Introducing%20Desistance%20-%20August%202013.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.clinks.org/sites/default/fil